33:48.727 --> 33:52.597 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," I'm
David Biello in Des Moines,
Iowa.

33:52.597 --> 33:57.802 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And a reminder:
Tomorrow, I will be reporting
from Iowa on the race for

33:57.802 --> 34:01.606 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the White House. Be sure to tune
to the "NewsHour" all weekend
and Monday for the latest on the

34:01.606 --> 34:04.309 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Iowa caucuses.

34:04.309 --> 34:08.680 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We will air at our regular time.
Plus, we will have a late-night
special report Monday

34:08.680 --> 34:24.796 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
night at 11:00 Eastern.

34:24.796 --> 34:29.601 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One of the key themes you hear
in this presidential campaign
is, why isn't the economy
growing

34:29.601 --> 34:34.005 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
faster and yielding even better
wages for workers? That question
isn't just a matter

34:34.005 --> 34:37.575 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
of debate among politicians.

34:37.575 --> 34:41.713 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Some economists are also
wondering if something
fundamental has changed in the
U.S. in recent

34:41.713 --> 34:43.548 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
decades.

34:43.548 --> 34:47.786 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That's the subject of tonight's
report by our economics
correspondent, Paul Solman.

34:47.786 --> 34:52.424 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's part of his series, Making
Sense, which airs Thursdays.

34:52.424 --> 34:57.462 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: President Obama's
last of State of the Union
featured this proud
proclamation:

34:57.462 --> 35:00.265 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BARACK OBAMA, President of the
United States: Anyone claiming
that America's economy is

35:00.265 --> 35:04.336 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
in decline is peddling fiction.

35:04.336 --> 35:09.474 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: But really? Tell
that to eminent economist Robert
Gordon, a Democrat, who's

35:09.474 --> 35:15.480 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
peddling a distinctly
nonfictional new book, "The Rise
and Fall of American Growth."

35:15.480 --> 35:18.316 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ROBERT GORDON, Author, "The Rise
and Fall of American Growth":
Did you know that the

35:18.316 --> 35:22.454 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
cable car dates back to 1870,
the beginning of what I call the
special century, when life

35:22.454 --> 35:25.857 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
was revolutionized in
the United States?

35:25.857 --> 35:33.865 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: A century that
ended in 1970, 46 years ago.
Gordon's thesis that slower

35:33.865 --> 35:40.438 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
growth is the new normal in the
U.S. has sparked a major debate
in economics the past few years.

35:40.438 --> 35:43.875 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
His book was a hot topic at this
year's meeting of the American
Economic Association in San

35:43.875 --> 35:45.176 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Francisco.

35:45.176 --> 35:48.880 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BOB SHILLER, Nobel Laureate:
It's what you call a magnum
opus.

35:48.880 --> 35:53.718 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: That's Nobel
laureate Bob Shiller, this
year's president of the group,
who organized

35:53.718 --> 35:59.224 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a session on the new book and
chaired it himself to spotlight
Gordon and his special century

35:59.224 --> 36:01.259 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
thesis.

36:01.259 --> 36:06.097 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROBERT GORDON: A century that
freed households from an
unremitting daily grind of
gainful

36:06.097 --> 36:11.803 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
manual labor, household
drudgery, darkness, isolation
and early death.

36:11.803 --> 36:16.274 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: There seems little
dispute in economics these days
that 1870 to 1970 was

36:16.274 --> 36:18.710 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
technologically special.

36:18.710 --> 36:24.516 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WOMAN: No one who hasn't cooked
over a wood stove by the light
of a kerosene lamp can

36:24.516 --> 36:24.949 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
really appreciate
what it all means.

36:24.949 --> 36:27.252 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: So it was an
amazing century, right?

36:27.252 --> 36:29.320 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ERIK BRYNJOLFSSON, Massachusetts
Institute of Technology: It was
an amazing century.

36:29.320 --> 36:32.390 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We took so much muscle power,
things that used to be done by
horses or by humans, and

36:32.390 --> 36:34.826 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
replaced it with machines.

36:34.826 --> 36:38.430 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: But MIT's Erik
Brynjolfsson doesn't buy the
argument that the U.S. economy's
best

36:38.430 --> 36:40.732 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
days are over.

36:40.732 --> 36:43.802 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ERIK BRYNJOLFSSON: We're now
just in the early stages of what
we sometimes call a second

36:43.802 --> 36:49.040 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
machine age, where we're
beginning to do the same things
for brainpower, things like
artificial

36:49.040 --> 36:52.544 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
intelligence, computers and big
data. And I think we're going to
see a productivity

36:52.544 --> 36:55.313 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
wave the likes of which we
have never seen before.

36:55.313 --> 37:00.819 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ROBERT GORDON: It's just a hope
that Erik has that these new
inventions of robots and

37:00.819 --> 37:04.756 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
artificial intelligence are
going to change the world on a
par with electricity and the

37:04.756 --> 37:07.625 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
internal combustion engine.

37:07.625 --> 37:11.396 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Just think of the benefits of
getting rid of the urban horse.
Think of all the horse

37:11.396 --> 37:15.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
droppings all over the street
that we no longer have to think
about and clean up.

37:15.400 --> 37:19.337 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: To counter those
who consider his cavalier
dismissal of high technology

37:19.337 --> 37:24.709 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
so much, well, horse manure,
Gordon took us on an intimate
show-and-tell.

37:24.709 --> 37:27.912 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ROBERT GORDON: Look at a few of
the things that were invented in
the special century

37:27.912 --> 37:33.418 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
after 1870, starting with the
electric light, the greatest
invention of all. And now let's

37:33.418 --> 37:38.123 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
look at two of the great
inventions of all time. First,
we have running water, which

37:38.123 --> 37:42.594 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
eliminated the need to carry
water into the house in pails.

37:42.594 --> 37:47.899 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then we have the flush
toilet, which eliminated the
need to go outside into the
bitter cold

37:47.899 --> 37:54.339 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to an outhouse. And here we have
a double invention, central
heating and air conditioning.

37:54.339 --> 38:00.278 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We have the telephone invented
in 1876. We have the television
set, partly invented here

38:00.278 --> 38:04.315 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in San Francisco by Philosophy
Farnsworth, and then look what
we have hidden down here,

38:04.315 --> 38:08.853 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a refrigerator, which eliminated
the contamination of food.

38:08.853 --> 38:13.791 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And here we have the Golden Gate
Bridge, an example of the
tremendous investment in
infrastructure

38:13.791 --> 38:16.661 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that made our economy grow so
fast in the middle of the 20th
century. This bridge was

38:16.661 --> 38:18.563 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
finished in 1937.

38:18.563 --> 38:25.837 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
NARRATOR: The Golden
Gate is bridged.

38:25.837 --> 38:27.138 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Put them all
together, says Gordon, and
there's been no comparable
stretch of

38:27.138 --> 38:31.609 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
economic growth before or since.

38:31.609 --> 38:37.916 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ROBERT GORDON: Here is the basic
point of my book. The early 20th
century, the middle

38:37.916 --> 38:43.421 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of the 20th century between 1920
and 1970, and all the years
since then, and the role

38:43.421 --> 38:48.426 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of innovation and technology is
that black area at the bottom.
And when we highlight

38:48.426 --> 38:52.363 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it we see that in the middle of
the 20th century, we were
growing three times faster than
we

38:52.363 --> 38:55.099 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
have been in the last 40 years.

38:55.099 --> 39:01.506 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: And not only were
the really big inventions
already on the market by 1970.

39:01.506 --> 39:06.644 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This footage of the 1962 Seattle
World's Fair suggests the ones
we consider big today were

39:06.644 --> 39:09.514 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
already in the works.

39:09.514 --> 39:14.552 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NARRATOR: One day, you may be
able to call home and
automatically turn off the oven
or,

39:14.552 --> 39:18.690 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
from a public telephone, water
the lawn during that dry spell
when you are many miles away

39:18.690 --> 39:21.759 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
on vacation. Sounds
fantastic, doesn't it?

39:21.759 --> 39:25.430 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Critics like
Brynjolfsson don't dispute the
wonders of the past. They just

39:25.430 --> 39:28.266 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
think we haven't
seen anything yet.

39:28.266 --> 39:31.669 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ERIK BRYNJOLFSSON: It's been
said that the greatest failing
of the human mind is the

39:31.669 --> 39:35.273 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
inability to understand the
exponential function. And that's
especially true in the computer

39:35.273 --> 39:39.344 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
era, where computer power
doubles about every 24 months or
so.

39:39.344 --> 39:44.148 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Exponential growth
like 2-4-8-16 and so on.

39:44.148 --> 39:48.119 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ERIK BRYNJOLFSSON: What that
does is, it leads us to
overestimate what's going to
happen

39:48.119 --> 39:50.622 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in the short run, because at
first it's happening fairly
slowly, but then we
underestimate what

39:50.622 --> 39:51.856 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
happens in the long run,
when things really take off.

39:51.856 --> 39:54.592 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Bob Gordon scoffs.

39:54.592 --> 39:57.962 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROBERT GORDON: But computers
have been riding this
exponential wave for the last 50
years,

39:57.962 --> 40:00.031 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
and it's not shown
up in productivity.

40:00.031 --> 40:04.535 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: In measured GDP
output per unit of labor, that
is.

40:04.535 --> 40:08.606 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ROBERT GORDON: We have gone from
the mainframe to the personal
computer to the smartphone,

40:08.606 --> 40:15.280 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and only in the late 1990s did
we see a revival of productivity
growth of the kind of magnitude

40:15.280 --> 40:18.416 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to match the great old days of
electricity and the invention of
the motorcar and the

40:18.416 --> 40:20.518 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
airplane.

40:20.518 --> 40:24.856 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Productivity, says
Gordon, has slowed to a crawl
for years now, what's called

40:24.856 --> 40:28.393 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
long-term or secular stagnation.

40:28.393 --> 40:31.963 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ERIK BRYNJOLFSSON: The last time
people were talking a lot about
stagnation was in the

40:31.963 --> 40:37.135 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
1930s. And guess what? The next
couple of decades were the best
decades ever for economic

40:37.135 --> 40:38.870 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
growth.

40:38.870 --> 40:43.608 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
PAUL SOLMAN: Admittedly,
Americans have been
techno-overoptimists before.

40:43.608 --> 40:49.147 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ACTOR: The 9000 series is the
most reliable computer ever
made. We are all foolproof and

40:49.147 --> 40:51.582 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
incapable of error.

40:51.582 --> 40:57.522 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: The year 2001 came
and went without any manned
space odysseys of note.

40:57.522 --> 41:00.258 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
ACTOR: Open the pod
bay doors, Hal.

41:00.258 --> 41:03.361 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Much less ones with
the likes of artificially
intelligent Hal.

41:03.361 --> 41:08.800 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ACTOR: I'm sorry, Dave. I'm
afraid I can't do that.

41:08.800 --> 41:14.706 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: But most striking
to us is the near-universal
agreement about the headwinds

41:14.706 --> 41:20.912 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
now facing U.S. economic growth:
problems in education, an aging
population, a huge

41:20.912 --> 41:27.018 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
national debt, and, most of
all, growing inequality.

41:27.018 --> 41:30.722 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Economic historian Greg Clark
said he's long been a
techno-optimist. But after
reading

41:30.722 --> 41:32.824 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Gordon's book:

41:32.824 --> 41:34.325 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
GREGORY CLARK, Economic
Historian, University of
California, Davis: I am actually
convinced

41:34.325 --> 41:38.830 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
now that the best of America is
behind us in terms of economic
growth.

41:38.830 --> 41:44.102 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Clark titled his
talk "Winter Is Coming," a nod
to the grim TV series about

41:44.102 --> 41:48.439 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
a more primitive time,
HBO's "Game of Thrones."

41:48.439 --> 41:53.778 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GREGORY CLARK: I titled it that
way because I was struck, when I
looked at the future

41:53.778 --> 41:58.583 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of the U.S. economy, how much it
was going to resemble the
medieval economy.

41:58.583 --> 42:00.952 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
PAUL SOLMAN: The
medieval economy?

42:00.952 --> 42:05.790 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GREGORY CLARK: The medieval
economy, in terms of the types
of jobs that people now are
doing,

42:05.790 --> 42:13.030 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
gardening, food preparing,
serving, cleaning, bricklaying,
carpentry. You could get someone

42:13.030 --> 42:17.402 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
from 1400, put them on the job
and in two hours, they'd be
perfectly functional.

42:17.402 --> 42:21.339 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Working, that
is, but hardly getting by.

42:21.339 --> 42:26.277 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And to Robert Gordon, the
connection between stagnant
wages and today's political
unease

42:26.277 --> 42:28.279 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
is obvious.

42:28.279 --> 42:33.351 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ROBERT GORDON: Because the heart
of slow wage growth is slow
productivity growth. And added

42:33.351 --> 42:37.622 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to that is the inequality that
is siphoning off the little
productivity that we have got

42:37.622 --> 42:40.625 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
into the top 1 percent. And so
the bottom 99 percent have good
reason to be resentful

42:40.625 --> 42:43.127 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
and anxious.

42:43.127 --> 42:46.931 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: For the "PBS
NewsHour," this is economics
correspondent Paul Solman,
reporting

42:46.931 --> 42:53.371 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
from San Francisco.

42:53.371 --> 43:05.349 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now to the
anniversary of the Challenger
shuttle tragedy, and how it
changed

43:05.349 --> 43:09.120 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
the U.S. space program
for years to come.

43:09.120 --> 43:14.058 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It was 30 years ago today when
we watched the Challenger
explode on live television

43:14.058 --> 43:19.030 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
just a little more than a minute
after it lifted off. All seven
people aboard, including

43:19.030 --> 43:25.169 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a high school teacher who became
the first ordinary citizen to go
into space, were killed.

43:25.169 --> 43:28.940 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
President Ronald Reagan was
supposed to deliver the State of
the Union speech that night.

43:28.940 --> 43:31.576 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Instead, he spoke to the
country from the Oval Office.

43:31.576 --> 43:35.746 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Here is some of what he said
in a video we produced.

43:35.746 --> 43:40.952 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MAN: Three, two, one, and
liftoff, liftoff of the 25th
space shuttle mission, and it

43:40.952 --> 43:43.020 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
has cleared the tower.

43:43.020 --> 43:46.123 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
MAN: Challenger, go
with throttle-up.

43:46.123 --> 43:51.629 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RONALD REAGAN, Former President
of the United States: Today is a
day for mourning and
remembering.

43:51.629 --> 43:56.767 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Nancy and I are pained to the
core by the tragedy of the
shuttle Challenger. We know

43:56.767 --> 44:01.739 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
we share this pain with all the
people of our country. This is
truly a national loss.

44:01.739 --> 44:04.842 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
WOMAN: Here comes the
flight crew now.

44:04.842 --> 44:08.112 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RONALD REAGAN: We have never
lost an astronaut, not in
flight. We have never had a
tragedy

44:08.112 --> 44:10.548 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
like this.

44:10.548 --> 44:16.053 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And perhaps we've forgotten the
courage it took for the crew of
the shuttle, but they,

44:16.053 --> 44:22.326 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the Challenger seven, were aware
of the dangers, but overcame
them and did their jobs
brilliantly.

44:22.326 --> 44:31.068 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We mourn seven heroes, Michael
Smith, Dick Scobee, Judith
Resnik, Ronald McNair, Ellison

44:31.068 --> 44:39.076 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Onizuka, Gregory Jarvis, and
Christa McAuliffe. We mourn
their loss as a nation together.

44:39.076 --> 44:43.080 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The crew of the space shuttle
Challenger honored us by the
manner in which they lived their

44:43.080 --> 44:50.021 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
lives. We will never forget
